      "issues": [
        {
          "code": "valence_giveaway",
          "distractor_index": 0,
          "note": "Original round-2 defects (stem-contradiction on the closing-date distractor, incoherent repair-estimate distractor) ARE resolved — both were removed. But the replacement set introduces a set-level valence giveaway: 'Establishing authority and directing the seller toward a cash offer quickly' is a pressure/rep-centered tactic, and all three distractors sit on that same pressure valence while the key is the only service/seller-centered option. Module 1 is titled Welcome and Mindset with the explicit theme 'put service before pressure'; a learner who knows only the module theme — not this card — eliminates all three and picks the key."
        },
        {
          "code": "valence_giveaway",
          "distractor_index": 1,
          "note": "'Creating urgency and securing commitment to the first solution presented' is a forced-yes/pressure tactic explicitly repudiated by the course (aligned decision not a forced yes; consulting means options, not pushing commitment). Same opposite-valence side as index 0; contributes to the all-distractors-opposite-valence pattern that makes the key derivable without lesson knowledge."
        },
        {
          "code": "stem_contradiction",
          "distractor_index": 2,
          "note": "'Demonstrating expertise and completing the conversation without follow-up questions' is in logical tension with the stem premise: leading with the seller's problem describes a question-driven discovery approach, so an outcome of completing the conversation WITHOUT follow-up questions reads incoherent under the stem's own terms — eliminable by stem logic alone. This is the third round in which a distractor in this entry is stem-eliminable (same defect class as both prior rejections). It also shares the pressure/performance valence of indexes 0-1."
        },
        {
          "code": "ambiguous_correctness",
          "distractor_index": null,
          "note": "Checker escalation after three failed authoring rounds: the module theme (service before pressure) makes the seller-centered key derivable from theme alone whenever distractors are wrong-valenced, and stem-compatible same-valence wrong answers keep collapsing into partial truths. Needs human authoring or a different question form."
        }
      ]
